    type: "Web Mapping Application",
    typeKeywords: ["Map", "Mapping Site", "Online Map", "Web Map"],
    description:
      "<p style='margin:revert; font-size:16px; color:rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family:&quot;Avenir Next&quot;, Avenir, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align:justify;'><span style='font-family:inherit; font-weight:revert; margin:revert;'><font size='3' style='font-family:inherit;'>The Homestead Act of 1862, signed by President Abraham Lincoln, is one of the most important laws passed that augmented the expansion of the Western territory with simultaneous displacement of Native Americans. The Act offered Americans an opportunity to own 160 acres of public land for a small filing fee and improve it over a span of five years. To make a claim, a homesteader had to be the head of household or 21 years of age and had to certify that they had never borne arms against the nation. The Act allowed citizens from different walks of life to own land.</font></span></p><p style='margin:revert; font-size:16px; color:rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family:&quot;Avenir Next&quot;, Avenir, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align:justify;'><font size='3' style='font-family:inherit;'><span style='font-family:inherit; font-weight:revert; margin:revert;'>The Homestead Act remained active for more than a century and resulted in the distribution of more than 275 million acres of land (approximately 1.6 million homestead settlements). </span><i>The app visualizes the history of homesteading over time and space in 30 American states from 1868 to 1961. Use the time slider to explore the percentage of land in the state claimed by homesteaders.</i></font></p><p style='margin:revert; font-size:16px; color:rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family:&quot;Avenir Next&quot;, Avenir, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, sans-serif; text-align:justify;'><font size='2' style='font-family:inherit;'><span style='font-family:inherit; font-weight:revert; margin:revert;'>Data Source: </span><font style='font-family:inherit;'>Homesteading the Plains: Toward a New History</font></font></p>",
